# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: differential-scanning-calorimetry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Calorimetry is performed with a calorimeter.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Scottish physician and scientist Joseph Black, who was the first to recognize the distinction between heat and temperature, is said to be the founder of the science of calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Indirect calorimetry calculates heat that living organisms produce by measuring either their production of carbon dioxide and nitrogen waste (frequently ammonia in aquatic organisms, or urea in terrestrial ones), or from their consumption of oxygen.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Lavoisier noted in 1780 that heat production can be predicted from oxygen consumption this way, using multiple regression.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The dynamic energy budget theory explains why this procedure is correct.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Heat generated by living organisms may also be measured by *direct calorimetry*, in which the entire organism is placed inside the calorimeter for the measurement.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] A widely used modern instrument is the differential scanning calorimeter, a device which allows thermal data to be obtained on small amounts of material.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] It involves heating the sample at a controlled rate and recording the heat flow either into or from the specimen.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The concept of heat has intrigued scientists for more than 2500 years.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] In the Graeco-Roman era, Plato and Aristotle regarded heat as a manifestation of fire.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Newton proposed that it was transmitted by vibrations of the particles of aether, while Descartes described it as an accelerated motion of air particles induced by light.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Robert Hooke viewed heat as a property of matter arising from the motion of its parts.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For centuries, the prevailing theory imagined heat as a self-repelling, weightless fluid called "caloric".
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The measurement of heat began to take shape about three centuries ago.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] In 1750, Georg Wilhelm Richmann formulated the first general calorimetric equation, later known as Richmann's law, allowing calculation of the equilibrium temperature of mixed substances of the same kind.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] A decade later, Joseph Black made a decisive contribution: in 1761, he discovered that adding heat to ice at its melting point or to boiling water did not change their temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] His identification of latent and specific heat marked the birth of thermodynamics and introduced the distinction between heat and temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] In 1782, Antoine Lavoisier and Pierre-Simon de la Place constructed the first ice-calorimeter, launching quantitative calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] At least one recent publication has called this calorie-metabolism theory into question.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Notably, the ice-calorimeter was first called *the machine* until the word *calorie* was coined in 1789.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The next major advance came from Sir Benjamin Thompson in the 1790s.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Observing heat generated during cannon boring under water, he concluded that heat must be a form of energy, not a material substance.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This idea was quantified by James Prescott Joule, who in the 1840s determined the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Using falling weights to drive a paddle in an insulated liquid, Joule demonstrated that 4.184 joules of work produce the same heating effect as one calorie, establishing a numerical link between mechanical work and thermal energy.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Around the same time, in 1840, the chemist Germain Henri Hess formulated Hess's law, showing that the total enthalpy change of a chemical reaction is independent of the reaction path.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This principle remains fundamental to modern thermochemistry and calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Finally, in the 1870s, Pierre Eugène Berthelot developed the first modern bomb calorimeter and introduced the concepts of endothermic and exothermic reactions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Calorimetry requires that a reference material that changes temperature have known definite thermal constitutive properties.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The classical rule, recognized by Clausius and Kelvin, is that the pressure exerted by the calorimetric material is fully and rapidly determined solely by its temperature and volume; this rule is for changes that do not involve phase change, such as melting of ice.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] There are many materials that do not comply with this rule, and for them, the present formula of classical calorimetry does not provide an adequate account.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The thermal response of the calorimetric material is fully described by its pressure $p\$ as the value of its constitutive function $p(V,T)\$ of just the volume $V\$ and the temperature $T\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] All increments are here required to be very small.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This calculation refers to a domain of volume and temperature of the body in which no phase change occurs, and there is only one phase present.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] An important assumption here is continuity of property relations.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] To determine this latent heat, the volume change is effectively the independently instrumentally varied quantity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This latent heat is not one of the widely used ones, but is of theoretical or conceptual interest.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The temperature is forced to change by exposure to a suitable heat bath.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This latent heat is one of the two widely used ones.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The latent heat with respect to volume is the heat required for unit increment in volume at constant temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] It can be said to be 'measured along an isotherm', and the pressure the material exerts is allowed to vary freely, according to its constitutive law $p=p(V,T)\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For a given material, it can have a positive or negative sign or exceptionally it can be zero, and this can depend on the temperature, as it does for water about 4 C.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The concept of latent heat with respect to volume was perhaps first recognized by Joseph Black in 1762.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The term 'latent heat of expansion' is also used.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The latent heat with respect to volume can also be called the 'latent energy with respect to volume'.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For all of these usages of 'latent heat', a more systematic terminology uses 'latent heat capacity'.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The heat capacity at constant volume is the heat required for unit increment in temperature at constant volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] It can be said to be 'measured along an isochor', and again, the pressure the material exerts is allowed to vary freely.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This means that for an increase in the temperature of a body without change of its volume, heat must be supplied to it.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This is consistent with common experience.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Quantities like $\delta Q\$ are sometimes called 'curve differentials', because they are measured along curves in the $(V,T)\$ surface.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Constant-volume calorimetry is calorimetry performed at a constant volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This involves the use of a constant-volume calorimeter.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Heat is still measured by the above-stated principle of calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This means that in a suitably constructed calorimeter, called a bomb calorimeter, the increment of volume $\delta V\$ can be made to vanish, $\delta V=0\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] From the above rule of calculation of heat with respect to volume, there follows one with respect to pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] An early calorimeter was that used by Laplace and Lavoisier, as shown in the figure above.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] It worked at constant temperature, and at atmospheric pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The latent heat involved was then not a latent heat with respect to volume or with respect to pressure, as in the above account for calorimetry without phase change.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The latent heat involved in this calorimeter was with respect to phase change, naturally occurring at constant temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This kind of calorimeter worked by measurement of mass of water produced by the melting of ice, which is a phase change.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This calculation is done by mathematical integration along the progression with respect to time.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This is because increments of heat are 'additive'; but this does not mean that heat is a conservative quantity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The idea that heat was a conservative quantity was invented by Lavoisier, and is called the 'caloric theory'; by the middle of the nineteenth century it was recognized as mistaken.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Written with the symbol $\Delta \$ , the quantity $\Delta Q(P(t_{1},t_{2}))\,$ is not at all restricted to be an increment with very small values; this is in contrast with $\delta Q\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This expression uses quantities such as ${\dot {Q}}(t)\$ which are defined in the section below headed 'Mathematical aspects of the above rules'.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The use of 'very small' quantities such as $\delta Q\$ is related to the physical requirement for the quantity $p(V,T)\$ to be 'rapidly determined' by $V\$ and $T\$ ; such 'rapid determination' refers to a physical process.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] These 'very small' quantities are used in the Leibniz approach to the infinitesimal calculus.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The Newton approach uses instead 'fluxions' such as ${\dot {V}}(t)=\left.{\frac {dV}{dt}}\right|_{t}$ , which makes it more obvious that $p(V,T)\$ must be 'rapidly determined'.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] denotes the time rate of change of temperature of the calorimetric material.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The increment $\delta Q\$ and the fluxion ${\dot {Q}}(t)\$ are obtained for a particular time $t\$ that determines the values of the quantities on the righthand sides of the above rules.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] But this is not a reason to expect that there should exist a mathematical function $Q(V,T)\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For this reason, the increment $\delta Q\$ is said to be an 'imperfect differential' or an 'inexact differential'.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Some books indicate this by writing $q\$ instead of $\delta Q\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Also, the notation *đQ* is used in some books.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Carelessness about this can lead to error.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The quantity $\Delta Q(P(t_{1},t_{2}))\$ is properly said to be a functional of the continuous joint progression $P(t_{1},t_{2})\$ of $V(t)\$ and $T(t)\$ , but, in the mathematical definition of a function, $\Delta Q(P(t_{1},t_{2}))\$ is not a function of $(V,T)\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Although the fluxion ${\dot {Q}}(t)\$ is defined here as a function of time $t\$ , the symbols $Q\$ and $Q(V,T)\$ respectively standing alone are not defined here.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The above rules refer only to suitable calorimetric materials.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The terms 'rapidly' and 'very small' call for empirical physical checking of the domain of validity of the above rules.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The above rules for the calculation of heat belong to pure calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] They make no reference to thermodynamics, and were mostly understood before the advent of thermodynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] They are the basis of the 'thermo' contribution to thermodynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The 'dynamics' contribution is based on the idea of work, which is not used in the above rules of calculation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Empirically, it is convenient to measure properties of calorimetric materials under experimentally controlled conditions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For measurements at experimentally controlled volume, one can use the assumption, stated above, that the pressure of the body of calorimetric material is can be expressed as a function of its volume and temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For measurements at experimentally controlled pressure, it is assumed that the volume $V\$ of the body of calorimetric material can be expressed as a function $V(T,p)\$ of its temperature $T\$ and pressure $p\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This assumption is related to, but is not the same as, the above used assumption that the pressure of the body of calorimetric material is known as a function of its volume and temperature; anomalous behaviour of materials can affect this relation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] For measurements at experimentally controlled temperature, it is again assumed that the volume $V\$ of the body of calorimetric material can be expressed as a function $V(T,p)\$ of its temperature $T\$ and pressure $p\$ , with the same provisos as mentioned just above.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Assuming that the rule $p=p(V,T)\$ is known, one can derive the function of ${\frac {\partial p}{\partial T}}\$ that is used above in the classical heat calculation with respect to pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Thermodynamics developed gradually over the first half of the nineteenth century, building on the above theory of calorimetry which had been worked out before it, and on other discoveries.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] In terms of thermodynamics, the internal energy $U\$ of the calorimetric material can be considered as the value of a function $U(V,T)\$ of $(V,T)\$ , with partial derivatives ${\frac {\partial U}{\partial V}}\$ and ${\frac {\partial U}{\partial T}}\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Calorimetry has a special benefit for thermodynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] It tells about the heat absorbed or emitted in the isothermal segment of a Carnot cycle.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] A Carnot cycle is a special kind of cyclic process affecting a body composed of material suitable for use in a heat engine.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Such a material is of the kind considered in calorimetry, as noted above, that exerts a pressure that is very rapidly determined just by temperature and volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Such a body is said to change reversibly.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] (4) another adiabatic change of volume from $V_{d}\$ back to $V_{a}\$ just such as to return the body to its starting temperature $T^{+}\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] This quantity is used by thermodynamics and is related in a special way to the net work done by the body during the Carnot cycle.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The net change of the body's internal energy during the Carnot cycle, $\Delta U(V_{a},V_{b};T^{+};V_{c},V_{d};T^{-})\$ , is equal to zero, because the material of the working body has the special properties noted above.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The quantity $C_{T}^{(V)}(V,T)\$ , the latent heat with respect to volume, belongs to classical calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] It accounts for the occurrence of energy transfer by work in a process in which heat is also transferred; the quantity, however, was considered before the relation between heat and work transfers was clarified by the invention of thermodynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] In the light of thermodynamics, the classical calorimetric quantity is revealed as being tightly linked to the calorimetric material's equation of state $p=p(V,T)\$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] From this, further mathematical and thermodynamic reasoning leads to another relation between classical calorimetric quantities.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] No work is performed in constant-volume calorimetry, so the heat measured equals the change in internal energy of the system.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] The heat capacity at constant volume is assumed to be independent of temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] Heat is measured by the principle of calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] In *constant-volume calorimetry* the pressure is not held constant.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] If there is a pressure difference between initial and final states, the heat measured needs adjustment to provide the *enthalpy change*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/calorimetry] is the unchanging volume of the sample chamber.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystallization occurs in two main phases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The first is nucleation, the appearance of a crystalline phase from either a supercooled liquid or a supersaturated solvent.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The second step is known as crystal growth, which is the increase in the size of particles and leads to a crystal state.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] An important feature of this step is that loose particles form layers at the crystal's surface and lodge themselves into open inconsistencies such as pores, cracks, etc.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystallization is also a chemical solid–liquid separation technique, in which mass transfer of a solute from the liquid solution to a pure solid crystalline phase occurs.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] In chemical engineering, crystallization occurs in a crystallizer.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystallization is therefore related to precipitation, although the result is not amorphous or disordered, but a crystal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The crystallization process consists of two major events, *nucleation* and *crystal growth* which are driven by thermodynamic properties as well as chemical properties.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] *Nucleation* is the step where the solute molecules or atoms dispersed in the solvent start to gather into clusters, on the microscopic scale (elevating solute concentration in a small region), that become stable under the current operating conditions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] These stable clusters constitute the nuclei.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Therefore, the clusters need to reach a critical size in order to become stable nuclei.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Such critical size is dictated by many different factors (temperature, supersaturation, etc.).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The *crystal growth* is the subsequent size increase of the nuclei that succeed in achieving the critical cluster size.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystal growth is a dynamic process occurring in equilibrium where solute molecules or atoms precipitate out of solution, and dissolve back into solution.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Supersaturation is one of the driving forces of crystallization, as the solubility of a species is an equilibrium process quantified by Ksp.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Depending upon the conditions, either nucleation or growth may be predominant over the other, dictating crystal size.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Many compounds have the ability to crystallize with some having different crystal structures, a phenomenon called polymorphism.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Certain polymorphs may be metastable, meaning that although it is not in thermodynamic equilibrium, it is kinetically stable and requires some input of energy to initiate a transformation to the equilibrium phase.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Each polymorph is in fact a different thermodynamic solid state and crystal polymorphs of the same compound exhibit different physical properties, such as dissolution rate, shape (angles between facets and facet growth rates), melting point, etc.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] For this reason, polymorphism is of major importance in industrial manufacture of crystalline products.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Additionally, crystal phases can sometimes be interconverted by varying factors such as temperature, such as in the transformation of anatase to rutile phases of titanium dioxide.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] There are many examples of natural process that involve crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystals can be formed by various methods, such as: cooling, evaporation, addition of a second solvent to reduce the solubility of the solute (technique known as antisolvent or drown-out), solvent layering, sublimation, changing the cation or anion, as well as other methods.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The formation of a supersaturated solution does not guarantee crystal formation, and often a seed crystal or scratching the glass is required to form nucleation sites.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] A typical laboratory technique for crystal formation is to dissolve the solid in a solution in which it is partially soluble, usually at high temperatures to obtain supersaturation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The hot mixture is then filtered to remove any insoluble impurities.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystals that form are then filtered and washed with a solvent in which they are not soluble, but is miscible with the mother liquor.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The process is then repeated to increase the purity in a technique known as recrystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] For biological molecules in which the solvent channels continue to be present to retain the three dimensional structure intact, microbatch crystallization under oil and vapor diffusion have been the common methods.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Equipment for the main industrial processes for crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] *Mixed-Suspension, Mixed-Product-Removal (MSMPR)*: MSMPR is used for much larger scale inorganic crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] MSMPR can crystalize solutions in a continuous manner.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] *Draft Tube and Baffle* *crystallizers*: Conceptualized in the late 1950s, DTB crystallizers contain an internal circulator that moves the solution upwards at a very low velocity, and a settling area in an annulus around the tank.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Large crystals rise and settle against the annulus continuously, while smaller crystals are filtered through a side-tube in the settling area, re-dissolved, and returned to the mother liquor to sustain supersaturation and promote large crystal growth.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The crystallization process appears to violate the second principle of thermodynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Whereas most processes that yield more orderly results are achieved by applying heat, crystals usually form at lower temperatures – especially by supercooling.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] However, the release of the heat of fusion during crystallization causes the entropy of the universe to increase, thus this principle remains unaltered.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The molecules within a pure, *perfect crystal*, when heated by an external source, will become liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This occurs at a sharply defined temperature (different for each type of crystal).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] As it liquifies, the complicated architecture of the crystal collapses.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Regarding crystals, there are no exceptions to this rule.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Similarly, when the molten crystal is cooled, the molecules will return to their crystalline form once the temperature falls beyond the turning point.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This is because the thermal randomization of the surroundings compensates for the loss of entropy that results from the reordering of molecules within the system.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Such liquids that crystallize on cooling are the exception rather than the rule.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The nature of the crystallization process is governed by both thermodynamic and kinetic factors, which can make it highly variable and difficult to control.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Factors such as impurity level, mixing regime, vessel design, and cooling profile can have a major impact on the size, number, and shape of crystals produced.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] As mentioned above, a crystal is formed following a well-defined pattern, or structure, dictated by forces acting at the molecular level.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] As a consequence, during its formation process the crystal is in an environment where the solute concentration reaches a certain critical value, before changing status.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Solid formation, impossible below the solubility threshold at the given temperature and pressure conditions, may then take place at a concentration higher than the theoretical solubility level.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The difference between the actual value of the solute concentration at the crystallization limit and the theoretical (static) solubility threshold is called supersaturation and is a fundamental factor in crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Nucleation is the initiation of a phase change in a small region, such as the formation of a solid crystal from a liquid solution.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] It is a consequence of rapid local fluctuations on a molecular scale in a homogeneous phase that is in a state of metastable equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Total nucleation is the sum effect of two categories of nucleation – primary and secondary.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Primary nucleation is the initial formation of a crystal where there are no other crystals present or where, if there are crystals present in the system, they do not have any influence on the process.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The first is homogeneous nucleation, which is nucleation that is not influenced in any way by solids.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] These solids include the walls of the crystallizer vessel and particles of any foreign substance.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The second category, then, is heterogeneous nucleation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This occurs when solid particles of foreign substances cause an increase in the rate of nucleation that would otherwise not be seen without the existence of these foreign particles.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Homogeneous nucleation rarely occurs in practice due to the high energy necessary to begin nucleation without a solid surface to catalyze the nucleation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] is an empirical exponent that can be as large as 10, but generally ranges between 3 and 4.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Secondary nucleation is the formation of nuclei attributable to the influence of the existing microscopic crystals in the magma.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] More simply put, secondary nucleation is when crystal growth is initiated with contact of other existing crystals or "seeds".
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The first type of known secondary crystallization is attributable to fluid shear, the other due to collisions between already existing crystals with either a solid surface of the crystallizer or with other crystals themselves.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Fluid-shear nucleation occurs when liquid travels across a crystal at a high speed, sweeping away nuclei that would otherwise be incorporated into a crystal, causing the swept-away nuclei to become new crystals.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Contact nucleation has been found to be the most effective and common method for nucleation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] is an empirical exponent that can range up to 5, but is generally 2.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Once the first small crystal, the nucleus, forms it acts as a convergence point (if unstable due to supersaturation) for molecules of solute touching – or adjacent to – the crystal so that it increases its own dimension in successive layers.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The pattern of growth resembles the rings of an onion, as shown in the picture, where each colour indicates the same mass of solute; this mass creates increasingly thin layers due to the increasing surface area of the growing crystal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The supersaturated solute mass the original nucleus may *capture* in a time unit is called the *growth rate* expressed in kg/(m2*h), and is a constant specific to the process.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Growth rate is influenced by several physical factors, such as surface tension of solution, pressure, temperature, relative crystal velocity in the solution, Reynolds number, and so forth.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The first value is a consequence of the physical characteristics of the solution, while the others define a difference between a well- and poorly designed crystallizer.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The appearance and size range of a crystalline product is extremely important in crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] If further processing of the crystals is desired, large crystals with uniform size are important for washing, filtering, transportation, and storage, because large crystals are easier to filter out of a solution than small crystals.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Also, larger crystals have a smaller surface area to volume ratio, leading to a higher purity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This higher purity is due to less retention of mother liquor which contains impurities, and a smaller loss of yield when the crystals are washed to remove the mother liquor.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] In special cases, for example during drug manufacturing in the pharmaceutical industry, small crystal sizes are often desired to improve drug dissolution rate and bio-availability.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The theoretical crystal size distribution can be estimated as a function of operating conditions with a fairly complicated mathematical process called population balance theory (using population balance equations).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This division is not really clear-cut, since hybrid systems exist, where cooling is performed through evaporation, thus obtaining at the same time a concentration of the solution.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] A crystallization process often referred to in chemical engineering is the fractional crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This is not a different process, rather a special application of one (or both) of the above.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Most chemical compounds, dissolved in most solvents, show the so-called *direct* solubility that is, the solubility threshold increases with temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] So, whenever the conditions are favorable, crystal formation results from simply cooling the solution.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Here *cooling* is a relative term: austenite crystals in a steel form well above 1000 °C.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] An example of this crystallization process is the production of Glauber's salt, a crystalline form of sodium sulfate.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] In the diagram, where equilibrium temperature is on the x-axis and equilibrium concentration (as mass percent of solute in saturated solution) in y-axis, it is clear that sulfate solubility quickly decreases below 32.5 °C.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The simplest cooling crystallizers are tanks provided with a mixer for internal circulation, where temperature decrease is obtained by heat exchange with an intermediate fluid circulating in a jacket.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] These simple machines are used in batch processes, as in processing of pharmaceuticals and are prone to scaling.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Batch processes normally provide a relatively variable quality of the product along with the batch.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The *Swenson-Walker* crystallizer is a model, specifically conceived by Swenson Co. around 1920, having a semicylindric horizontal hollow trough in which a hollow screw conveyor or some hollow discs, in which a refrigerating fluid is circulated, plunge during rotation on a longitudinal axis.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The refrigerating fluid is sometimes also circulated in a jacket around the trough.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Crystals precipitate on the cold surfaces of the screw/discs, from which they are removed by scrapers and settle on the bottom of the trough.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The screw, if provided, pushes the slurry towards a discharge port.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] In simple words, the liquid is cooled by evaporating a part of it.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] In the sugar industry, vertical cooling crystallizers are used to exhaust the molasses in the last crystallization stage downstream of vacuum pans, prior to centrifugation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The massecuite enters the crystallizers at the top, and cooling water is pumped through pipes in counterflow.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Another option is to obtain, at an approximately constant temperature, the precipitation of the crystals by increasing the solute concentration above the solubility threshold.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] To obtain this, the solute/solvent mass ratio is increased using the technique of evaporation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This process is insensitive to change in temperature (as long as hydration state remains unchanged).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] All considerations on control of crystallization parameters are the same as for the cooling models.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Most industrial crystallizers are of the evaporative type, such as the very large sodium chloride and sucrose units, whose production accounts for more than 50% of the total world production of crystals.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The most common type is the *forced circulation* (FC) model (see evaporator).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The Oslo, mentioned above, is a refining of the evaporative forced circulation crystallizer, now equipped with a large crystals settling zone to increase the retention time (usually low in the FC) and to roughly separate heavy slurry zones from clear liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Evaporative crystallizers tend to yield larger average crystal size and narrows the crystal size distribution curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] Whichever the form of the crystallizer, to achieve an effective process control it is important to control the retention time and the crystal mass, to obtain the optimum conditions in terms of crystal specific surface and the fastest possible growth.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] This can be achieved by a separation – to put it simply – of the crystals from the liquid mass, in order to manage the two flows in a different way.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] The practical way is to perform a gravity settling to be able to extract (and possibly recycle separately) the (almost) clear liquid, while managing the mass flow around the crystallizer to obtain a precise slurry density elsewhere.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] A typical example is the DTB (*Draft Tube and Baffle*) crystallizer, an idea of Richard Chisum Bennett (a Swenson engineer and later President of Swenson) at the end of the 1950s.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/crystallization] A quasi-perfect control of all parameters is achieved as DTF crystallizers offer superior control over crystal size and characteristics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Generally, the temperature program for a DSC analysis is designed such that the sample holder temperature increases linearly as a function of time.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The reference sample should have a well-defined heat capacity over the range of temperatures to be scanned.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Additionally, the reference sample must be stable, of high purity, and must not experience much change across the temperature scan.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Typically, reference standards have been metals such as indium, tin, bismuth, and lead, but other standards such as polyethylene and fatty acids have been proposed to study polymers and organic compounds, respectively.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] O'Neill in 1962, and introduced commercially at the 1963 Pittsburgh Conference on Analytical Chemistry and Applied Spectroscopy.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The first adiabatic differential scanning calorimeter that could be used in biochemistry was developed by P.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Monaselidze in 1964 at Institute of Physics in Tbilisi, Georgia.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The term DSC was coined to describe this instrument, which measures energy directly and allows precise measurements of heat capacity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] There are two main types of DSC: *Heat-flux DSC* which measures the difference in heat flux between the sample and a reference (which gives it the alternative name *Multi-Cell DSC*) and *Power differential DSC* which measures the difference in power supplied to the sample and a reference.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] With Heat-flux DSC, the changes in heat flow are calculated by integrating the ΔTref- curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For this kind of experiment, a sample and a reference crucible are placed on a sample holder with integrated temperature sensors for temperature measurement of the crucibles.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This arrangement is located in a temperature-controlled oven.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Unlike the traditional design, the special feature of heat-flux DSC is that it uses flat temperature sensors placed vertically around a flat heater.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This setup makes it possible to have a small, light, and low-heat capacity structure while still working like a regular DSC oven.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For this kind of setup, also known as *Power compensating DSC*, the sample and reference crucible are placed in thermally insulated furnaces and not next to each other in the same furnace as in heat-flux-DSC experiments.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Then the temperature of both chambers is controlled so that the same temperature is always present on both sides.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The electrical power that is required to obtain and maintain this state is then recorded rather than the temperature difference between the two crucibles.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The 2000s have witnessed the rapid development of Fast-scan DSC (FSC), a novel calorimetric technique that employs micromachined sensors.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The key advances of this technique are the ultrahigh scanning rate, which can be as high as 106 K/s, and the ultrahigh sensitivity, with a heat capacity resolution typically better than 1 nJ/K.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Nanocalorimetry has attracted much attention in materials science, where it is applied to perform quantitative analysis of rapid phase transitions, particularly on fast cooling.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Another emerging area of application of FSC is physical chemistry, with a focus on the thermophysical properties of thermally labile compounds.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Quantities like fusion temperature, fusion enthalpy, sublimation, and vaporization pressures, and enthalpies of such molecules became available.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] When performing Temperature Modulated DSC (TMDSC, MDSC), the underlying linear heating rate is superimposed by a sinusoidal temperature variation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The benefit of this procedure is the ability to separate overlapping DSC effects by calculating the reversing and the non-reversing signals.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The reversing heat flow is related to the changes in specific heat capacity (→ glass transition) while the non-reversing heat flow corresponds to time-dependent phenomena such as curing, dehydration and relaxation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The basic principle underlying this technique is that when the sample undergoes a physical transformation such as phase transitions, more or less heat will need to flow to it than the reference to maintain both at the same temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Whether less or more heat must flow to the sample depends on whether the process is exothermic or endothermic.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For example, as a solid sample melts to a liquid, it will require more heat flowing to the sample to increase its temperature at the same rate as the reference.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This is due to the absorption of heat by the sample as it undergoes the endothermic phase transition from solid to liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Likewise, as the sample undergoes exothermic processes (such as crystallization) less heat is required to raise the sample temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] By observing the difference in heat flow between the sample and reference, differential scanning calorimeters are able to measure the amount of heat absorbed or released during such transitions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC may also be used to observe more subtle physical changes, such as glass transitions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] It is widely used in industrial settings as a quality control instrument due to its applicability in evaluating sample purity and for studying polymer curing.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] An alternative technique, which shares much in common with DSC, is differential thermal analysis (DTA).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In this technique it is the heat flow to the sample and reference that remains the same rather than the temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] When the sample and reference are heated identically, phase changes and other thermal processes cause a difference in temperature between the sample and reference.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Both DSC and DTA provide similar information.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC measures the energy required to keep both the reference and the sample at the same temperature whereas DTA measures the difference in temperature between the sample and the reference when the same amount of energy has been introduced into both.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The result of a DSC experiment is a curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The y-axis is the differential heat flux ${\dot {q}}$ , measured in units of $J/s$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The *x*-axis is either time, or the temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Both conventions for the x-axis are the same when the temperature is growing linearly with time, as it is usually the case.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For the *sign* of ${\dot {q}}$ , there are two different conventions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] One convention defines ${\dot {q}}$ so that ${\dot {q}}>0$ for exothermic process in the sample.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For example, in the convention where exothermic process corresponds to ${\dot {q}}>0$ , the plot would show a negative spike as temperature increases beyond the melting point, since melting is an endothermic process.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Conversely, it would show a positive spike as temperature drops below the melting point.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This curve can be used to calculate enthalpies of transitions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This is done by taking the time-integral of peak corresponding to a given transition: $\Delta H=KA$ where $\Delta H$ is the enthalpy of transition, A is the area under the curve, and K is a certain constant called the "calorimetric constant".
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] That particular constant varies from instrument to instrument, and can be measured by performing DSC on a calibration sample whose enthalpies of transition is known accurately.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This curve can also be used to calculate the molar specific heat capacity as a function of temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] To obtain this, one perform DSC with two samples.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] One sample is a reference sample whose molar specific heat capacity $c_{ref}$ is known accurately, and the other sample's c needs to be measured.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Then, after performing the DSC, we have $c(T)={\frac {1}{n}}\left({\frac {\dot {q}}{\dot {T}}}+n_{ref}c_{ref}(T)\right)$ where n is the mole of the sample, $n_{ref}$ is the mole of the reference, and ${\dot {T}}$ is the rate at which temperature increases, with units of $T/s$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Differential scanning calorimetry can be used to measure a number of characteristic properties of a sample.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Using this technique it is possible to observe fusion and crystallization events as well as glass transition temperatures *Tg*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC can also be used to study oxidation, as well as other chemical reactions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Glass transitions may occur as the temperature of an amorphous solid is increased.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] These transitions appear as a step in the baseline of the recorded DSC signal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This is due to the sample undergoing a change in heat capacity; no formal phase change occurs.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] As the temperature increases, an amorphous solid will become less viscous.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] At some point the molecules may obtain enough freedom of motion to spontaneously arrange themselves into a crystalline form.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This is known as the crystallization temperature (*Tc*).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This transition from amorphous solid to crystalline solid is an exothermic process, and results in a peak in the DSC signal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] As the temperature increases the sample eventually reaches its melting temperature (*Tm*).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The melting process results in an endothermic peak in the DSC curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The ability to determine transition temperatures and enthalpies makes DSC a valuable tool in producing phase diagrams for various chemical systems.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Differential scanning calorimetry can also be used to obtain valuable thermodynamics information about proteins.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The thermodynamics analysis of proteins can reveal important information about the global structure of proteins, and protein/ligand interaction.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For example, many mutations lower the stability of proteins, while ligand binding usually increases protein stability.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Using DSC, this stability can be measured by obtaining Gibbs Free Energy values at any given temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This allows researchers to compare the free energy of unfolding between ligand-free protein and protein-ligand complex, or wild type and mutant proteins.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC can also be used in studying protein/lipid interactions, nucleotides, drug-lipid interactions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In studying protein denaturation using DSC, the thermal melt should be at least to some degree reversible, as the thermodynamics calculations rely on chemical equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] There are various experimental and environmental parameters to consider during DSC measurements.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Exemplary potential issues are briefly discussed in the following sections.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] All statements in these paragraphs are based on the books of Gabbott and Brown.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC measurements without crucibles promote the thermal transfer towards the sample and are possible if the DSC is designed for this purpose.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Measurements without crucible should only be conducted with chemically stable materials at low temperatures, as otherwise there may be contamination or damage of the calorimeter.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The safer way is to use a crucible, which is specified for the desired temperatures and does not react with the sample material (e.g. alumina, gold or platinum crucibles).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] If the sample is likely to evolve volatiles or is in the liquid state, the crucible should be sealed to prevent contamination.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] However, if the crucible is sealed, increasing pressure and possible measurement artefacts due to deformation of the crucible must be considered.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In this case, crucibles with very small holes (∅~50 μm) or crucibles that can withstand very high pressures should be used.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The sample should be in good contact with the crucible surface.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Therefore, the contact surface of a solid bulk sample should be plane parallel.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For DSC measurements with powders, stronger signal might be observed for finer powders due to the enlarged contact surface.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The minimum sample mass depends on the transformation to be analyzed.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] A small sample mass (~10 mg) is sufficient if the released or consumed heat during the transformation is high enough.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Heavier samples could be used to obtain transformation associated with low heat release or consumption, as larger samples also enlarge the obtained peaks.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] However, the increasing sample size might worsen the resolution due to thermal gradients which may evolve during heating.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] If the peaks are very small, it is possible to enlarge them by increasing the scan rate.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Due to the faster scan rate, more energy is released or consumed in a shorter time which leads to higher and therefore more distinct peaks.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] However, faster scan rates lead to poor temperature resolution because of thermal lag.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Due to this thermal lag, two phase transformations (or chemical reactions) occurring in a narrow temperature range might overlap.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Generally, heating or cooling rates are too high to detect equilibrium transitions, so there is always a shift to higher or lower temperatures compared to phase diagrams representing equilibrium conditions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Purge gas is used to control the sample environment, in order to reduce signal noise and to prevent contamination.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Mostly nitrogen is used and for temperatures above 600 °C, argon can be utilized to minimize heat loss due to the low thermal conductivity of argon.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Air or pure oxygen can be used for oxidative tests like oxidative induction time and He is used for very low temperatures due to the low boiling temperature (~4.2K at 101.325 kPa ).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The technique is widely used across a range of applications, both as a routine quality test and as a research tool.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The equipment is easy to calibrate, using low melting indium at 156.5985 °C for example, and is a rapid and reliable method of thermal analysis.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC is used widely for examining polymeric materials to determine their thermal transitions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Important thermal transitions include the glass transition temperature (*T*g), crystallization temperature (*T*c), and melting temperature (*T*m).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The observed thermal transitions can be utilized to compare materials, although the transitions alone do not uniquely identify composition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The composition of unknown materials may be completed using complementary techniques such as IR spectroscopy.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Melting points and glass transition temperatures for most polymers are available from standard compilations, and the method can show polymer degradation by the lowering of the expected melting temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] *Tm* depends on the molecular weight of the polymer and thermal history.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The percent crystalline content of a polymer can be estimated from the crystallization/melting peaks of the DSC graph using reference heats of fusion found in the literature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC can also be used to study thermal degradation of polymers using an approach such as Oxidative Onset Temperature/Time (OOT); however, the user risks contamination of the DSC cell, which can be problematic.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Thermogravimetric Analysis (TGA) may be more useful for decomposition behavior determination.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Impurities in polymers can be determined by examining thermograms for anomalous peaks, and plasticisers can be detected at their characteristic boiling points.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In addition, examination of minor events in first heat thermal analysis data can be useful as these apparently "anomalous peaks" can in fact also be representative of process or storage thermal history of the material or polymer physical aging.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Comparison of first and second heat data collected at consistent heating rates can allow the analyst to learn about both polymer processing history and material properties.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC is used in the study of liquid crystals.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] As some forms of matter go from solid to liquid they go through a third state, which displays properties of both phases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This anisotropic liquid is known as a liquid crystalline or mesomorphous state.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Using DSC, it is possible to observe the small energy changes that occur as matter transitions from a solid to a liquid crystal and from a liquid crystal to an isotropic liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Using differential scanning calorimetry to study the stability to oxidation of samples generally requires an airtight sample chamber.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] It can be used to determine the oxidative-induction time (OIT) of a sample.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Such tests are usually done isothermally (at constant temperature) by changing the atmosphere of the sample.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] First, the sample is brought to the desired test temperature under an inert atmosphere, usually nitrogen.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Any oxidation that occurs is observed as a deviation in the baseline.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Such analysis can be used to determine the stability and optimum storage conditions for a material or compound.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC equipment can also be used to determine the Oxidative-Onset Temperature (OOT) of a material.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In this test a sample (and a reference) are exposed to an oxygen atmosphere and subjected to a constant rate of heating (typically from 50 to 300 °C).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The DSC heat flow curve will deviate when the reaction with oxygen begins (the reaction being either exothermic or endothermic).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Both OIT and OOT tests are used as a tools for determining the activity of antioxidants.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC makes a reasonable initial safety screening tool.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In this mode the sample will be housed in a non-reactive crucible (often gold or gold-plated steel), and which will be able to withstand pressure (typically up to 100 bar).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The presence of an exothermic event can then be used to assess the stability of a substance to heat.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] A much more accurate data set can be obtained from an adiabatic calorimeter, but such a test may take 2–3 days from ambient at a rate of a 3 °C increment per half-hour.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] DSC is widely used in the pharmaceutical and polymer industries.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For the polymer chemist, DSC is a handy tool for studying curing processes, which allows the fine tuning of polymer properties.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] The cross-linking of polymer molecules that occurs in the curing process is exothermic, resulting in a negative peak in the DSC curve that usually appears soon after the glass transition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] In the pharmaceutical industry it is necessary to have well-characterized drug compounds in order to define processing parameters.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] For instance, if it is necessary to deliver a drug in the amorphous form, it is desirable to process the drug at temperatures below those at which crystallization can occur.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Freezing-point depression can be used as a **purity analysis** tool when analysed by differential scanning calorimetry.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] This is possible because the temperature range over which a mixture of compounds melts is dependent on their relative amounts.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/differential-scanning-calorimetry] Consequently, less pure compounds will exhibit a broadened melting peak that begins at lower temperature than a pure compound.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The enthalpy of fusion is the amount of energy required to convert one mole of solid into liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] For example, when melting 1 kg of ice (at 0 °C under a wide range of pressures), 333.55 kJ of energy is absorbed with no temperature change.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The **heat of solidification** (when a substance changes from liquid to solid) is equal in magnitude and opposite in sign.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] This energy includes the contribution required to make room for any associated change in volume by displacing its environment against ambient pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The temperature at which the phase transition occurs is the melting point or the freezing point, according to context.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] By convention, the pressure is assumed to be 1 atm (101.325 kPa) unless otherwise specified.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The enthalpy of fusion is a latent heat, because, while melting, the heat energy needed to change the substance from solid to liquid does not cause any increase in temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] Temperature remains constant during the freezing or melting process, and only begins to change again (assuming the energy input or removal (cooling) continues) after the phase change is complete.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The latent heat of fusion is the enthalpy change of any amount of substance when it melts.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] When the heat of fusion is referenced to a unit of mass, it is usually called the **specific heat of fusion**, while the **molar heat of fusion** refers to the enthalpy change per amount of substance in moles.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The liquid phase has a higher internal energy than the solid phase.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] This means energy must be supplied to a solid in order to melt it and energy is released from a liquid when it freezes, because the molecules in the liquid experience weaker intermolecular forces and so have a higher potential energy (a kind of bond-dissociation energy for intermolecular forces).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] When liquid water is cooled, its temperature falls steadily until it drops just below the line of freezing point at 0 °C.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The temperature then remains constant at the freezing point while the water crystallizes.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] Once the water is completely frozen, its temperature resumes a colder trend.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The enthalpy of fusion is almost always a positive quantity; helium is the only known exception.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] Helium-3 has a negative enthalpy of fusion at temperatures below 0.3 K.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] Helium-4 also has a very slightly negative enthalpy of fusion below 0.77 K (−272.380 °C).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] This means that, at appropriate constant pressures, these substances freeze with the addition of heat.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] In the case of 4He, this pressure range is between 24.992 and 25.00 atm (2,533 kPa).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] These values are mostly from the CRC *Handbook of Chemistry and Physics*, 62nd edition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The conversion between cal/g and J/g in the above table uses the thermochemical calorie (calth) = 4.184 joules rather than the International Steam Table calorie (calINT) = 4.1868 joules.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] The heat of fusion can also be used to predict solubility for solids in liquids.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] which is a deviation from the real solubility (240 g/L) of 11%.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] This error can be reduced when an additional heat capacity parameter is taken into account.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/enthalpy-of-fusion] with $R\,$ the gas constant and $T\,$ the temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The **glass–liquid transition**, or **glass transition**, is the gradual and reversible transition in amorphous materials (or in amorphous regions within semicrystalline materials) from a hard and relatively brittle "glassy" state into a viscous or "rubbery" state as the temperature is increased.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] An amorphous solid that exhibits a glass transition is called a glass.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The reverse transition, achieved by supercooling a viscous liquid into the glass state, is called vitrification.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The **glass-transition temperature** *T*g of a material characterizes the range of temperatures over which this glass transition occurs (as an experimental definition, typically marked as 100 s of relaxation time).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] It is always lower than the melting temperature, *T*m, of the crystalline state of the material, if one exists, because the glass is a higher energy state (or enthalpy at constant pressure) than the corresponding crystal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Hard plastics like polystyrene and poly(methyl methacrylate) are used well below their glass transition temperatures, i.e., when they are in their glassy state.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Their *T*g values are both at around 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Rubber elastomers like polyisoprene and polyisobutylene are used above their *T*g, that is, in the rubbery state, where they are soft and flexible; crosslinking prevents free flow of their molecules, thus endowing rubber with a set shape at room temperature (as opposed to a viscous liquid).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Despite the change in the physical properties of a material through its glass transition, the transition is not considered a phase transition; rather it is a phenomenon extending over a range of temperature and defined by one of several conventions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Such conventions include a constant cooling rate (20 kelvins per minute (36 °F/min)) and a viscosity threshold of 1012 Pa·s, among others.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Upon cooling or heating through this glass-transition range, the material also exhibits a smooth step in the thermal-expansion coefficient and in the specific heat, with the location of these effects again being dependent on the history of the material.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The question of whether some phase transition underlies the glass transition is a matter of ongoing research.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The glass transition of a liquid to a solid-like state may occur with either cooling or compression.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The transition comprises a smooth increase in the viscosity of a material by as much as 17 orders of magnitude within a temperature range of 500 K without any pronounced change in material structure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This transition is in contrast to the freezing or crystallization transition, which is a first-order phase transition in the Ehrenfest classification and involves discontinuities in thermodynamic and dynamic properties such as volume, energy, and viscosity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In many materials that normally undergo a freezing transition, rapid cooling will avoid this phase transition and instead result in a glass transition at some lower temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Other materials, such as many polymers, lack a well defined crystalline state and easily form glasses, even upon very slow cooling or compression.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The tendency for a material to form a glass while quenched is called glass forming ability.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This ability depends on the composition of the material and can be predicted by the rigidity theory.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Below the transition temperature range, the glassy structure does not relax in accordance with the cooling rate used.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The expansion coefficient for the glassy state is roughly equivalent to that of the crystalline solid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] If slower cooling rates are used, the increased time for structural relaxation (or intermolecular rearrangement) to occur may result in a higher density glass product.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Similarly, by annealing (and thus allowing for slow structural relaxation) the glass structure in time approaches an equilibrium density corresponding to the supercooled liquid at this same temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] *T*g is located at the intersection between the cooling curve (volume versus temperature) for the glassy state and the supercooled liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The configuration of the glass in this temperature range changes slowly with time towards the equilibrium structure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The principle of the minimization of the Gibbs free energy provides the thermodynamic driving force necessary for the eventual change.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] At somewhat higher temperatures than *T*g, the structure corresponding to equilibrium at any temperature is achieved quite rapidly.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In contrast, at considerably lower temperatures, the configuration of the glass remains sensibly stable over increasingly extended periods of time.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Thus, the liquid-glass transition is not a transition between states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] It is widely believed that the true equilibrium state is always crystalline.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Glass is believed to exist in a kinetically locked state, and its entropy, density, and so on, depend on the thermal history.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Therefore, the glass transition is primarily a dynamic phenomenon.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Time and temperature are interchangeable quantities (to some extent) when dealing with glasses, a fact often expressed in the time–temperature superposition principle.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] On cooling a liquid, *internal degrees of freedom successively fall out of equilibrium*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] However, there is a longstanding debate whether there is an underlying second-order phase transition in the hypothetical limit of infinitely long relaxation times.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In anisotropic-particle fluids, such as ellipsoid fluids, different degrees of freedom can fall out of equilibrium separately.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Calculations based on mode-coupling theory for the glass transition predicted, for hard ellipsoids, an orientational, or rotational, glass transition in which particle orientations become arrested while center-of-mass motion can remain quasi-ergodic.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Molecular dynamics simulations of a soft ellipsoid fluid later reproduced this behaviour, supporting the view that colloidal liquid glass is a rotationally arrested state distinct from the conventional glassy state described in this article, in which translation motion is arrested.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As a result of the fluctuating input of thermal energy into the liquid matrix, the harmonics of the oscillations are constantly disturbed and temporary cavities ("free volume") are created between the elements, the number and size of which depend on the temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The glass transition temperature *T*g0 defined in this way is a fixed material constant of the disordered (non-crystalline) state that is dependent only on the pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As a result of the increasing inertia of the molecular matrix when approaching *T*g0, the setting of the thermal equilibrium is successively delayed, so that the usual measuring methods for determining the glass transition temperature in principle deliver *T*g values that are too high.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In principle, the slower the temperature change rate is set during the measurement, the closer the measured *T*g value *T*g0 approaches.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Techniques such as dynamic mechanical analysis can be used to measure the glass transition temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The definition of the glass and the glass transition are not settled, and many definitions have been proposed over the past century.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Franz Simon: Glass is a rigid material obtained from freezing-in a supercooled liquid in a narrow temperature range.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Zachariasen: Glass is a topologically disordered network, with short range order equivalent to that in the corresponding crystal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Glass is a "frozen liquid" (i.e., liquids where ergodicity has been broken), which spontaneously relax towards the supercooled liquid state over a long enough time.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Glasses are thermodynamically non-equilibrium kinetically stabilized amorphous solids, in which the molecular disorder and the thermodynamic properties corresponding to the state of the respective under-cooled melt at a temperature *T** are frozen-in.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Hereby *T** differs from the actual temperature *T*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Glass is a nonequilibrium, non-crystalline condensed state of matter that exhibits a glass transition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The structure of glasses is similar to that of their parent supercooled liquids (SCL), and they spontaneously relax toward the SCL state.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Their ultimate fate is to solidify, i.e., crystallize.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Refer to the figure on the bottom right plotting the heat capacity as a function of temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In this context, *T*g is the temperature corresponding to point A on the curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Different operational definitions of the glass transition temperature *T*g are in use, and several of them are endorsed as accepted scientific standards.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Nevertheless, all definitions are arbitrary, and all yield different numeric results: at best, values of *T*g for a given substance agree within a few kelvins.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] One definition refers to the viscosity, fixing *T*g at a value of 1013 poise (or 1012 Pa·s).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As evidenced experimentally, this value is close to the annealing point of many glasses.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In contrast to viscosity, the thermal expansion, heat capacity, shear modulus, and many other properties of inorganic glasses show a relatively sudden change at the glass transition temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Any such step or kink can be used to define *T*g.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] To make this definition reproducible, the cooling or heating rate must be specified.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The most frequently used definition of *T*g uses the energy release on heating in differential scanning calorimetry (DSC, see figure).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Typically, the sample is first cooled with 10 K/min and then heated with that same speed.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Yet another definition of *T*g uses the kink in dilatometry (a.k.a. thermal expansion): refer to the figure on the top right.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Here, heating rates of 3–5 K/min (5.4–9.0 °F/min) are common.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The linear sections below and above *T*g are colored green.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] *T*g is the temperature at the intersection of the red regression lines.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Summarized below are *T*g values characteristic of certain classes of materials.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Dry nylon-6 has a glass transition temperature of 47 °C (117 °F).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Nylon-6,6 in the dry state has a glass transition temperature of about 70 °C (158 °F).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Polyethylene has a glass transition range of −130 to −80 °C (−202 to −112 °F).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The above are only approximate values, as the glass transition temperature depends on the cooling rate and molecular weight distribution and could be influenced by additives.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] For a semi-crystalline material, such as polyethylene that is 60–80% crystalline at room temperature, the quoted glass transition refers to what happens to the amorphous part of the material upon cooling.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In 1971, Zeller and Pohl discovered that when glass is at a very low temperature ~1K, its specific heat has a linear component: $c\approx c_{1}T+c_{3}T^{3}$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This is an unusual effect, because crystal material typically has $c\propto T^{3}$ , as in the Debye model.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This was explained by the two-level system hypothesis, which states that a glass is populated by two-level systems, which look like a double potential well separated by a wall.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The wall is high enough such that resonance tunneling does not occur, but thermal tunneling does occur.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Namely, if the two wells have energy difference $\Delta E\sim k_{B}T$ , then a particle in one well can tunnel to the other well by thermal interaction with the environment.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Consider a single two-level system that is not frozen-out, whose energy gap is $\Delta E=O(1/\beta )$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] It is in a Boltzmann distribution, so its average energy $={\frac {\beta \Delta E}{e^{\beta \Delta E}-1}}\beta ^{-1}$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Now, assume that the two-level systems are all quenched, so that each $\Delta E$ varies little with temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In that case, we can write $n(\Delta E)$ as the density of states with energy gap $\Delta E$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] We also assume that $n(\Delta E)$ is positive and smooth near $\Delta E\approx 0$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The effect is that the average energy in these two-level systems is ${\bar {E}}\sim T^{2}$ , leading to a $\partial _{T}{\bar {E}}\propto T$ term.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In experimental measurements, the specific heat capacity of glass is measured at different temperatures, and a $(T^{2},c/T)$ graph is plotted.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Assuming that $c\approx c_{1}T+c_{3}T^{3}$ , the graph should show $c/T\approx c_{1}+c_{3}T^{2}$ , that is, a straight line with slope showing the typical Debye-like heat capacity, and a vertical intercept showing the anomalous linear component.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Modern studies of glass-forming materials suggest that the slowing of dynamics near the glass-transition temperature is accompanied by increasing spatial heterogeneity in molecular motion.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Experimental and simulation studies suggest that molecular motion near the glass-transition temperature becomes spatially heterogeneous.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Instead of all segments slowing down uniformly, regions of relatively high mobility coexist with regions that are significantly less mobile, a phenomenon known as dynamic heterogeneity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As temperature approaches the glass-transition temperature, structural relaxation increasingly occurs through cooperative rearrangements involving groups of molecules or polymer segments, and the size of these cooperatively rearranging regions grows as the temperature decreases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Experimental evidence for dynamic heterogeneity has been obtained using techniques such as dielectric spectroscopy, multidimensional nuclear magnetic resonance, and single-molecule fluorescence measurements, all of which reveal spatial variations in relaxation dynamics near the glass transition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Molecular dynamics simulations similarly show spatially correlated motion and string-like rearrangements of particles in supercooled liquids and polymer systems approaching the glass transition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Dynamic heterogeneity has been proposed as an explanation for several features of glass-forming polymers, including non-exponential relaxation behavior, deviations from time–temperature superposition, and departures from simple free-volume descriptions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] These observations support the view that the glass transition is governed by cooperative dynamics rather than purely local segmental motion.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As a liquid is supercooled, the difference in entropy between the liquid and solid phase decreases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] By extrapolating the heat capacity of the supercooled liquid below its glass transition temperature, it is possible to calculate the temperature at which the difference in entropies becomes zero.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This temperature has been named the **Kauzmann temperature**.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] If a liquid could be supercooled below its Kauzmann temperature, and it did indeed display a lower entropy than the crystal phase, this would be paradoxical, as the liquid phase should have the same vibrational entropy, but much higher positional entropy, as the crystal phase.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This is the **Kauzmann paradox**, still not definitively resolved.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] There are many possible resolutions to the Kauzmann paradox.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Kauzmann himself resolved the entropy paradox by postulating that all supercooled liquids must crystallize before the Kauzmann temperature is reached.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Perhaps at the Kauzmann temperature, glass reaches an ideal glass *phase*, which is still amorphous, but has a long-range amorphous order which decreases its overall entropy to that of the crystal.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The ideal glass would be a true phase of matter.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The ideal glass is hypothesized, but cannot be observed naturally, as it would take too long to form.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Something approaching an ideal glass has been observed as "ultrastable glass" formed by vapor deposition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Perhaps there must be a phase transition before the entropy of the liquid decreases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In this scenario, the transition temperature is known as the *calorimetric ideal glass transition temperature* *T*0c.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In this view, the glass transition is not merely a kinetic effect, i.e. merely the result of fast cooling of a melt, but there is an underlying thermodynamic basis for glass formation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Perhaps the heat capacity of the supercooled liquid near the Kauzmann temperature smoothly decreases to a smaller value.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Perhaps first order phase transition to another liquid state occurs before the Kauzmann temperature with the heat capacity of this new state being less than that obtained by extrapolation from higher temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Time temperature superposition curve is a very powerful tool for the analysis of polymeric and rheological materials near the glass transition temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] One of the key uses of time temperature superposition (TTS) curves it to extrapolate the long term viscoelastic behavior of materials using the experimental data for the short term viscoelastic behavior of materials.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Therefore, it can provide key information for the design of polymeric materials over varying time scales and temperature scales (including the glass transition temperature.).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As a class of materials, TTS curves are very useful for understanding the behavior of polymeric materials because of their viscoelastic behavior where the flow and the deformation of the material is dependent on both the time and temperature of the material.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] For example, consider the behavior of a typical polymer subjected to a constant load.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] You would expect the strain/ deformation of the materials increases with time as the system tends to minimize local stresses by rearranging the molecular configuration.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Therefore, any short term measurements of the mechanical performance will provide a significantly lower or higher value depending on the property being measured.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] One method to determine the desired properties/ mechanical performance of the material is to study the behavior of the material at the exact temperature or time period that is of interest.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] However, if the time periods or temperatures required are very high, this method can quickly become very expensive in terms of time consumed and the cost.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Therefore, TTS curves provide an excellent tool to effectively predict the long term rheology of polymeric materials utilizing data for their short term behavior.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Time temperature superposition curves, which is also known as the method of reduced variables is based on two key principles/ assumptions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The first assumption is that an increase in temperature results in an increase in the frequency with which molecular rearrangements occur in viscoelastic materials.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Therefore, at high temperatures, the deformation and strain will vary at a much higher rate than at relatively low temperatures.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The second assumption is that there is a direct equivalency between the temperature and time (frequency).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In other words, the effects of increasing the temperature are directly equivalent to the effects of increasing the time scale in terms of their impact on the viscoelastic behavior of polymeric materials.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Therefore, if the deformation and strain behavior of a polymeric material are collected over a small time period at a high temperature, the resulting data can be shifted to determine the behavior of the material for a specific temperature over a much larger time scale.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This resultant curve which is determined after the shifting is known as the master curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] There are numerous different models which can be utilized to determine the amount of shift required to project the experimental curve in order to arrive at the master curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] However, the two most common models are the Williams Landels Ferry (WLF) model and the Arrhenius equation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The figure above shows a general time temperature superposition plot where the x axis is defined as the log(time) and the y axis is defined as the creep compliance.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Typically, y axis is either creep compliance or the elastic/ storage modulus (G').
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] From the figure above, it can be observed that the short term creep plots are shifted along the x-axis in order to obtain the master curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This x-axis shift can be determined using the WLF equation or the Arrhenius equation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The equation above describes the WLF equation where log At represents the x-axis shift required to obtain the master curve.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The reference temperature is the temperature at which the master curve is obtained whereas the other temperature variable T represents the temperature at which the short-term creep compliance data is collected.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The Williams Landels Ferry is most useful and accurate for understanding the time - temperature behavior of polymeric materials near the glass transition region because of the in-built assumptions of the model.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The WLF equation is based on the free volume theory of materials for glass transitions.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The first is that there is a linear, increasing relationship between the fractional free volume of the material and the temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The second assumption is that as the free volume of the material increases, the viscosity drops rapidly as there is more volume for particles to move (easier flow).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Within free volume theory, the empirical constants 𝐶1 and 𝐶2 in the Williams Landels Ferry equation can be interpreted in terms of the temperature dependence of fractional free volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Molecular mobility in polymers is assumed to depend exponentially on the inverse of the available fractional free volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] If the fractional free volume increases approximately linearly with temperature above the glass-transition temperature 𝑇𝑔, the constants 𝐶1 and 𝐶2 can be related to the fractional free volume at 𝑇𝑔 and the thermal expansion coefficient of the free volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The other model to determine the shift is the Arrhenius model which is more accurate for temperatures further away from the glass transition region.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The equation below describes the Arrhenius model where E is the activation energy and R is the ideal gas constant.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The temperature variables T and Tref refer to the measurement temperature and the reference temperature respectively.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Another important use of the Arrhenius model is to determine the activation energy of a polymeric material near the glass transition temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Although the WLF equation is a more accurate near the glass transition temperature, it can directly be utilized to estimate the activation energy of the material.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Silica (the chemical compound SiO2) has a number of distinct crystalline forms in addition to the quartz structure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Nearly all of the crystalline forms involve tetrahedral SiO4 units linked together by *shared vertices* in different arrangements (stishovite, composed of linked SiO6 octahedra, is the main exception).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Si-O bond lengths vary between the different crystal forms.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The Si-O-Si bond angle also varies from 140° in α-tridymite to 144° in α-quartz to 180° in β-tridymite.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Any deviations from these standard parameters constitute microstructural differences or variations that represent an approach to an amorphous, vitreous or glassy solid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The transition temperature *T*g in silicates is related to the energy required to break and re-form covalent bonds in an amorphous (or random network) lattice of covalent bonds.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The *T*g is clearly influenced by the chemistry of the glass.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] For example, addition of elements such as B, Na, K or Ca to a silica glass, which have a valency less than 4, helps in breaking up the network structure, thus reducing the *T*g.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Alternatively, P, which has a valency of 5, helps to reinforce an ordered lattice, and thus increases the *T*g.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] For strong melts such as Si*O*2 the percolation threshold in the above equation is the universal Scher–Zallen critical density in the 3-D space e.g.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] *f*c = 0.15, however for fragile materials the percolation thresholds are material-dependent and *f*c ≪ 1.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The enthalpy *H*d and the entropy *S*d of configurons – broken bonds can be found from available experimental data on viscosity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] On the surface of SiO2 films, scanning tunneling microscopy has resolved clusters of ca.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] 5 SiO2 in diameter that move in a two-state fashion on a time scale of minutes.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This is much faster than dynamics in the bulk, but in agreement with models that compare bulk and surface dynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In polymers the glass transition temperature, *T*g, is often expressed as the temperature at which the Gibbs free energy is such that the activation energy for the cooperative movement of 50 or so elements of the polymer is exceeded .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This allows molecular chains to slide past each other when a force is applied.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] From this definition, we can see that the introduction of relatively stiff chemical groups (such as benzene rings) will interfere with the flowing process and hence increase *T*g.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The stiffness of thermoplastics decreases due to this effect (see figure.) When the glass temperature has been reached, the stiffness stays the same for a while, i.e., at or near *E*2, until the temperature exceeds *T*m, and the material melts.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This region is called the rubber plateau.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In ironing, a fabric is heated through this transition so that the polymer chains become mobile.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The weight of the iron then imposes a preferred orientation.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] *T*g can be significantly decreased by addition of plasticizers into the polymer matrix.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Smaller molecules of plasticizer embed themselves between the polymer chains, increasing the spacing and free volume, and allowing them to move past one another even at lower temperatures.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Addition of plasticizer can effectively take control over polymer chain dynamics and dominate the amounts of the associated free volume so that the increased mobility of polymer ends is not apparent.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The addition of nonreactive side groups to a polymer can also make the chains stand off from one another, reducing *T*g.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] If a plastic with some desirable properties has a *T*g that is too high, it can sometimes be combined with another in a copolymer or composite material with a *T*g below the temperature of intended use.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Note that some plastics are used at high temperatures, e.g., in automobile engines, and others at low temperatures.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In viscoelastic materials, the presence of liquid-like behavior depends on the properties of and so varies with rate of applied load, i.e., how quickly a force is applied.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The silicone toy Silly Putty behaves quite differently depending on the time rate of applying a force: pull slowly and it flows, acting as a heavily viscous liquid; hit it with a hammer and it shatters, acting as a glass.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] On cooling, rubber undergoes a *liquid-glass transition*, which has also been called a *rubber-glass transition*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Polymer blending is a process in which two or more polymers are mixed together in order to create a new polymer with properties which are significantly different from the properties of the individual polymers.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The blending process can result in enhanced properties like superior strength or flexibility for a variety of applications like packaging, automotive parts and electronics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] There are various different classifications of polymer blends but in the discussion of the effect on glass transitions I will classify polymer blends as miscible and immiscible.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Miscibility refers to the mixing of the individual polymers at a molecular level.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] While miscible polymers mix favorably, immiscible polymers remain separate within the blend at a molecular level.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The miscibility of polymers has an impact on the glass transition region of the polymer blends.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Typically, for immiscible polymer blends, the glass transition temperature of the polymer doesn't change with the composition and it maintains the same glass transition temperature region as the bulk value of the polymer.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Most polymers are thermodynamically immiscible in nature due to their low configurational entropy of mixing.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Immiscible polymer blends are commonly produced using a technique called melt processing, which allows for production at a very low cost.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] At the molecular level, the phases in the blend of the individual polymers remain separate which is why the individual polymers maintain the same glass transition temperature / region as in their pure form.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In immiscible polymer blends, the separation of the phases for the individual polymers results in distinct glass transition temperature for the individual phases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Using either differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) or Dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA), the glass transition temperature of immiscible polymer blends can be revealed.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The results should show two or more distinct peaks depending on the number of separate phases in the immiscible polymer blend.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The presence of this distinct and individual glass transition temperature peaks indicates phase separation and can also be utilized to classify whether a polymer blend is immiscible or not.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] On the other hand, for miscible polymer blends in which the individual polymers mix favorably and completely, there is a single glass transition temperature which is typical in between the glass transition temperatures of the individual polymer Tg values.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] However, the glass transition temperature of the doesn't always have to be in between the individual Tg values.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The glass transition temperature of the miscible polymer blend is influenced by the composition and individual Tg values of the polymers.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The flory-fox equation/ model can be used to estimate the glass transition temperature of a miscible polymer blend to a good degree of accuracy when there are strong interactions between the individual polymers.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The fox model assumes that the mixing is ideal and that the chains are fully interspersed, which is why it only works accurately when there are strong interactions between the individual polymers.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The equation below describes the Fox equation where w is the weight fraction of the individual polymer and Tg represents the glass transition temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Bulk metallic glasses (BMGs) are intrinsically amorphous alloys.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] But while traditional amorphous alloys are typically formed at high cooling rates in order to suppress the nucleation of the crystalline phases, BMGs can be formed at lower critical cooling rates.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The high cooling rates needed for the formation of traditional amorphous alloys restricts the form of the finished product to powders, films, depositions and ribbons.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In comparison to the wide range of different types of glasses, BMGs have superior properties in terms of amorphous character and high mechanical strength.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] However, the most unique characteristic of BMGs is their glass transition behavior.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] As metallic glasses are cooled from high to low temperatures, they transform from a supercooled liquid state into a glassy state and vice versa.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Scientifically, metallic glasses are defined as amorphous alloys which exhibit a glass transition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This glass transition allows the materials to have a high strength at low temperatures and a very high flexibility at high temperatures due to the abrupt change in the physical and thermal properties of the material at the glass transition temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Regardless of the atomic configurations, it has been generally accepted by experts that the disorder of metallic glass can only be conserved down to a certain length scale.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Atoms in metallic glasses tend to form short range order in which the local nearest neighbor environment of each atom is similar to other equivalent atoms, but this regularity doesn't persist over an appreciable distance.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Due to the fact that good glass formers have a higher density than ordinary amorphous alloys with high critical cooling rates, it is recommended to have a composition with high packing density for good glass forming ability.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The figure 1c shows a differential scanning calorimetry of a bulk metallic glass sample, illustrating the glass transition and the presence of a wide supercooled liquid region.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The supercooled liquid region is defined in terms of the glass transition temperature (Tg) and the crystallization temperature (Tx).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The glass transition temperature represents the temperature below which the material becomes a rigid amorphous solid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Between the glass transition temperature and the crystallization temperature the material is in a supercooled liquid state.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] A wider supercooled liquid region allows easier formation of glass without unwanted crystallization and increases the probability of forming a more stable amorphous structure during rapid cooling.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Finally, the supercooled liquid region gives the material polymer-like forming capabilities (i.e. shaped, molded or formed like thermoplastics) while exhibiting the superior performance characteristics of metals at higher temperatures.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The supercooled liquid region is the key property of metallic glasses that makes it useful for applications such as biomedical implants.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Molecular motion in condensed matter can be represented by a Fourier series whose physical interpretation consists of a superposition of longitudinal and transverse waves of atomic displacement with varying directions and wavelengths.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In monatomic systems, these waves are called *density fluctuations*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Thus, thermal motion in liquids can be decomposed into elementary longitudinal vibrations (or acoustic phonons) while transverse vibrations (or shear waves) were originally described only in elastic solids exhibiting the highly ordered crystalline state of matter.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] In other words, simple liquids cannot support an applied force in the form of a shearing stress, and will yield mechanically via macroscopic plastic deformation (or viscous flow).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Furthermore, the fact that a solid deforms locally while retaining its rigidity – while a liquid yields to macroscopic viscous flow in response to the application of an applied shearing force – is accepted by many as the mechanical distinction between the two.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The inadequacies of this conclusion, however, were pointed out by Frenkel in his revision of the kinetic theory of solids and the theory of elasticity in liquids.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This revision follows directly from the continuous characteristic of the viscoelastic crossover from the liquid state into the solid one when the transition is not accompanied by crystallization—ergo the supercooled viscous liquid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Thus we see the intimate correlation between transverse acoustic phonons (or shear waves) and the onset of rigidity upon vitrification, as described by Bartenev in his mechanical description of the vitrification process.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The velocities of longitudinal acoustic phonons in condensed matter are directly responsible for the thermal conductivity that levels out temperature differentials between compressed and expanded volume elements.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Kittel proposed that the behavior of glasses is interpreted in terms of an approximately constant "mean free path" for lattice phonons, and that the value of the mean free path is of the order of magnitude of the scale of disorder in the molecular structure of a liquid or solid.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The thermal phonon mean free paths or relaxation lengths of a number of glass formers have been plotted versus the glass transition temperature, indicating a linear relationship between the two.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] This has suggested a new criterion for glass formation based on the value of the phonon mean free path.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] It has often been suggested that heat transport in dielectric solids occurs through elastic vibrations of the lattice, and that this transport is limited by elastic scattering of acoustic phonons by lattice defects (e.g. randomly spaced vacancies).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] These predictions were confirmed by experiments on commercial glasses and glass ceramics, where mean free paths were apparently limited by "internal boundary scattering" to length scales of 10–100 micrometres (0.00039–0.00394 in).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The influence of thermal phonons and their interaction with electronic structure is a topic that was appropriately introduced in a discussion of the resistance of liquid metals.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Lindemann's theory of melting is referenced, and it is suggested that the drop in conductivity in going from the crystalline to the liquid state is due to the increased scattering of conduction electrons as a result of the increased amplitude of atomic vibration.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Such theories of localization have been applied to transport in metallic glasses, where the mean free path of the electrons is very small (on the order of the interatomic spacing).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The formation of a non-crystalline form of a gold-silicon alloy by the method of splat quenching from the melt led to further considerations of the influence of electronic structure on glass forming ability, based on the properties of the metallic bond.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Other work indicates that the mobility of localized electrons is enhanced by the presence of dynamic phonon modes.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] One claim against such a model is that if chemical bonds are important, the nearly free electron models should not be applicable.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] However, if the model includes the buildup of a charge distribution between all pairs of atoms just like a chemical bond (e.g., silicon, when a band is just filled with electrons) then it should apply to solids.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Thus, if the electrical conductivity is low, the mean free path of the electrons is very short.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] The electrons will only be sensitive to the short-range order in the glass since they do not get a chance to scatter from atoms spaced at large distances.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Since the short-range order is similar in glasses and crystals, the electronic energies should be similar in these two states.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] For alloys with lower resistivity and longer electronic mean free paths, the electrons could begin to sense that there is disorder in the glass, and this would raise their energies and destabilize the glass with respect to crystallization.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Thus, the glass formation tendencies of certain alloys may therefore be due in part to the fact that the electron mean free paths are very short, so that only the short-range order is ever important for the energy of the electrons.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] It has also been argued that glass formation in metallic systems is related to the "softness" of the interaction potential between unlike atoms.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Some authors, emphasizing the strong similarities between the local structure of the glass and the corresponding crystal, suggest that chemical bonding helps to stabilize the amorphous structure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Other authors have suggested that the electronic structure yields its influence on glass formation through the directional properties of bonds.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Non-crystallinity is thus favored in elements with a large number of polymorphic forms and a high degree of bonding anisotropy.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/glass-transition] Crystallization becomes more unlikely as bonding anisotropy is increased from isotropic metallic to anisotropic metallic to covalent bonding, thus suggesting a relationship between the group number in the periodic table and the glass forming ability in elemental solids.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The corresponding intensive property is the specific heat capacity, found by dividing the heat capacity of an object by its mass.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Dividing the heat capacity by the amount of substance in moles yields its molar heat capacity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The volumetric heat capacity measures the heat capacity per volume.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In architecture and civil engineering, the heat capacity of a building is often referred to as its *thermal mass*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity of an object, denoted by C , is the limit $C=\lim _{\Delta T\to 0}{\frac {Q}{\Delta T}},$ where Q is the amount of heat that must be added to the object (of mass *M*) in order to raise its temperature by $\Delta T$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The value of this parameter usually varies considerably depending on the starting temperature T of the object and the pressure p applied to it.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In particular, it typically varies dramatically with phase transitions such as melting or vaporization (see enthalpy of fusion and enthalpy of vaporization).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Therefore, it is considered a function $C(p,T)$ of those two variables.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The variation can be ignored in contexts when working with objects in narrow ranges of temperature and pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] For example, the heat capacity of a block of iron weighing one pound is about 204 J/K when measured from a starting temperature *T* = 25 °C and *P* = 1 atm of pressure.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] That approximate value is adequate for temperatures between 15 °C and 35 °C, and surrounding pressures from 0 to 10 atmospheres, because the exact value varies very little in those ranges.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] One can trust that the same heat input of 204 J will raise the temperature of the block from 15 °C to 16 °C, or from 34 °C to 35 °C, with negligible error.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] At constant pressure, heat supplied to the system contributes to both the work done and the change in internal energy, according to the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] where the final equality follows from the appropriate Maxwell relations, and is commonly used as the definition of the isobaric heat capacity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] A system undergoing a process at constant volume implies that no expansion work is done, so the heat supplied contributes only to the change in internal energy.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity obtained this way is denoted $C_{V}.$ The value of $C_{V}$ is always less than the value of $C_{p}$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] where $N_{f}$ is the number of degrees of freedom of each individual particle in the gas, and $N_{i}=N_{f}-3$ is the number of internal degrees of freedom, where the number 3 comes from the three translational degrees of freedom (for a gas in 3D space).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] This means that a monoatomic ideal gas (with zero internal degrees of freedom) will have isochoric heat capacity $C_{v}={\frac {3nR}{2}}$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Heat capacity of a system undergoing phase transition is infinite, because the heat is utilized in changing the state of the material rather than raising the overall temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Given an isochoric system, $C_{v}=\left({\frac {\partial U}{\partial T}}\right)_{N,V}$ , which can be rewritten as $\left.dU\right|_{N,V=const}=C_{v}dT$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity may be well-defined even for heterogeneous objects, with separate parts made of different materials; such as an electric motor, a crucible with some metal, or a whole building.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In many cases, the (isobaric) heat capacity of such objects can be computed by simply adding together the (isobaric) heat capacities of the individual parts.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] However, this computation is valid only when all parts of the object are at the same external pressure before and after the measurement.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] For example, when heating an amount of gas in an elastic container, its volume *and pressure* will both increase, even if the atmospheric pressure outside the container is kept constant.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Therefore, the effective heat capacity of the gas, in that situation, will have a value intermediate between its isobaric and isochoric capacities $C_{p}$ and $C_{V}$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The heat energy that is supplied may end up as kinetic energy (energy of motion) and potential energy (energy stored in force fields), both at macroscopic and atomic scales.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Then the change in temperature will depend on the particular path that the system followed through its phase space between the initial and final states.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Namely, one must somehow specify how the positions, velocities, pressures, volumes, etc. changed between the initial and final states; and use the general tools of thermodynamics to predict the system's reaction to a small energy input.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The "constant volume" and "constant pressure" heating modes are just two among infinitely many paths that a simple homogeneous system can follow.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity can usually be measured by the method implied by its definition: start with the object at a known uniform temperature, add a known amount of heat energy to it, wait for its temperature to become uniform, and measure the change in its temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] This method can give moderately accurate values for many solids; however, it cannot provide very precise measurements, especially for gases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The SI unit for heat capacity of an object is joule per kelvin (J/K or J⋅K−1).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Since an increment of temperature of one degree Celsius is the same as an increment of one kelvin, that is the same unit as J/°C.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity of an object is an amount of energy divided by a temperature change, which has the dimension L2⋅M⋅T−2⋅Θ−1.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Therefore, the SI unit J/K is equivalent to kilogram meter squared per second squared per kelvin (kg⋅m2⋅s−2⋅K−1 ).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In those contexts, the unit of heat capacity is 1 BTU/°R ≈ 1900 J/K.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] The BTU was in fact defined so that the average heat capacity of one pound of water would be 1 BTU/°F.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In this regard, with respect to mass, note conversion of 1 Btu/lb⋅°R ≈ 4,187 J/kg⋅K and the calorie (below).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In chemistry, heat amounts are often measured in calories.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Most physical systems exhibit a positive heat capacity; constant-volume and constant-pressure heat capacities, rigorously defined as partial derivatives, are always positive for homogeneous bodies.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] However, even though it can seem paradoxical at first, there are some systems for which the heat capacity $Q/\Delta T$ is *negative*.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Examples include a reversibly and nearly adiabatically expanding ideal gas, which cools, $\Delta T<0$ , while a small amount of heat $Q>0$ is put in, or combusting methane with increasing temperature, $\Delta T>0$ , and giving off heat, $Q<0$ .
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Others are inhomogeneous systems that do not meet the strict definition of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] They include gravitating objects such as stars and galaxies, and also some nano-scale clusters of a few tens of atoms close to a phase transition.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] A negative heat capacity can result in a negative temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] If the system loses energy, for example, by radiating energy into space, the average kinetic energy actually increases.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] If a temperature is defined by the average kinetic energy, then the system therefore can be said to have a negative heat capacity.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] A more extreme version of this occurs with black holes.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] According to black-hole thermodynamics, the more mass and energy a black hole absorbs, the colder it becomes.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In contrast, if it is a net emitter of energy, through Hawking radiation, it will become hotter and hotter until it boils away.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] According to the second law of thermodynamics, when two systems with different temperatures interact via a purely thermal connection, heat will flow from the hotter system to the cooler one (this can also be understood from a statistical point of view).
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Therefore, if such systems have equal temperatures, they are at thermal equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] However, this equilibrium is stable only if the systems have *positive* heat capacities.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] For such systems, when heat flows from a higher-temperature system to a lower-temperature one, the temperature of the first decreases and that of the latter increases, so that both approach equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] In contrast, for systems with *negative* heat capacities, the temperature of the hotter system will further increase as it loses heat, and that of the colder will further decrease, so that they will move farther from equilibrium.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] This means that the equilibrium is unstable.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] For example, according to theory, the smaller (less massive) a black hole is, the smaller its Schwarzschild radius will be, and therefore the greater the curvature of its event horizon will be, as well as its temperature.
[src:differential-scanning-calorimetry/heat-capacity] Thus, the smaller the black hole, the more thermal radiation it will emit and the more quickly it will evaporate by Hawking radiation.
